comment: Unsure; difficult to judge the meaning in sentence 1
Unsure; difficult to judge the meaning in sentence 2
Unsure; I don't understand the usage in sentence 1 but it is definitely different from the usage in sentence 2
For sentence 2, I assume the bolded “head” is part of the prepositional phrase “at the head of thine army”

A rating of 3 would also be appropriate, but I think that both uses of “head” are more linked by being derivants of the anatomical head than by their meaning “at the beginning/top of”. I chose 2 because of this semantic distance.
The second sentence confuses me because 6,000 human heads could not fit into a mail-bag. I’m guessing that these “heads” are possibly images of people’s heads on stamps.
